tps://plato.stanford.edu/entries/hume-freewill/ \"Hume on Free Will\"] by Paul Russell\n* {{curlie|Society/Philosophy/Metaphysics/Free_Will_and_Determinism|Free Will and Determinism}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070825055350/http://www.rep.routledge.com/article/V014 \"Free Will\"] by [[Galen Strawson]] in [[Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150627161032/http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06259a.htm \"Free Will\"] in [[Catholic Encyclopedia]]\n* [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uctytho/dfwIntroIndex.htm The Determinism and Freedom Philosophy Website] edited by [[Ted Honderich]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150427115321/http://www.themontrealreview.com/2009/Freedom-and-the-laws-of-nature.php \"Freedom and the Laws of Nature\"] by Steven Horst (The Montr\u00e9al Review)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150520132731/http://skepdic.com/freewill.html The Skeptics Dictionary on 'free will' ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150921100429/http://www.earlymoderntexts.com/f_edwards.html Jonathan Edwards's Freedom of the Will, slightly modified for easier reading]\n\n{{Liberty}}\n{{metaphysics}}\n{{ethics}}\n{{Time travel}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{citizendium|title=Free will}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Free will}}\n[[Category:Action (philosophy)]]\n[[Category:Causality]]\n[[Category:Concepts in ethics]]\n[[Category:Concepts in metaphysics]]\n[[Category:Free will| ]]\n[[Category:Philosophical problems]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of life]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of religion]]\n[[Category:Religious ethics]]\n", "name_user": "DayronPL", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNeuroscience and neurophilosophy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_will"}
{"title_page": "Zenodotus", "text_new": "{{about|the grammarian|the Neoplatonist philosopher|Zenodotus (philosopher)|the Stoic philosopher|Zenodotus (Stoic)|}}\n\n'''Zenodotus''' ({{lang-grc-gre|\u0396\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}}) was a [[Greek language|Greek]] grammarian, [[literary critic]], [[Homeric scholarship|Homeric scholar]], and the first [[librarian]] of the [[Library of Alexandria]].{{efn|name=\"Two Others}} A native of [[Ephesus]] (today, the village of [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sel%C3%A7uk Sel\u0188uk] in western Turkey) and a pupil of [[Philitas of Cos]], he lived during the reigns of the first two [[Ptolemaic dynasty|Ptolemies]], and was at the height of his reputation about 280 BC.\n\n==Biography==\nZenodotus was the first superintendent of the [[Library of Alexandria]] and the first critical editor ({{lang|grc|\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b8\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2}} ''diorth\u014dtes'') of [[Homer]]. In 284 BC the Ptolemaic court appointed Zenodotus as first Director of the library and also the official tutor to the royal children. His colleagues in the librarianship were [[Alexander Aetolus|Alexander of Aetolia]] and [[Lycophron of Chalcis]], to whom were allotted the tragic and comic writers respectively, Homer and other epic poets being assigned to Zenodotus.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=973}}\n\nAlthough he has been reproached with arbitrariness and an insufficient knowledge of Greek, his recension undoubtedly laid a sound foundation for future criticism. Having collated the different manuscripts in the library, he expunged or obelized doubtful verses, transposed or altered lines, and introduced new readings. It is probable that he was responsible for the division of the Homeric poems into twenty-four books each, and possibly was the author of the calculation of the days of the ''Iliad'' in the ''[[Tabula Iliaca]]''.<ref>Zenodotus, of Ephesus. (1995). In Merriam Webster's Encyclopedia of Literature. Springfield, MA: Merriam-Webster.</ref>\n\nHe does not appear to have written any regular commentary on Homer, but his Homeric {{lang|grc|\u03b3\u03bb\u1ff6\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03b9}} (''[[wikt:\u03b3\u03bb\u1ff6\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1|gl\u014dssai]]'', \"lists of unusual words, [[gloss (annotation)|glosses]]\") probably formed the source of the explanations of Homer attributed by the grammarians to Zenodotus. He also lectured upon [[Hesiod]], [[Anacreon (poet)|Anacreon]] and [[Pindar]], if he did not publish editions of them. He is further called an epic poet by the ''[[Suda]],'' and three epigrams in the ''[[Greek Anthology]]'' are assigned to him.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=973}}\n\nIn addition to his other scholarly work, Zenodotus introduced an organization system on the materials in the [[Library of Alexandria]] whereby texts were assigned to different rooms based on their subject matter- verse or prose, literary or scientific, and the various sub-classifications within each. Within their subjects, Zenodotus organized the works [[Alphabetical order|alphabetically]] by the first letter of the name of their author. The principle of alphabetic organization was introduced by Zenodotus.<ref>Casson, L. (2001). Libraries in the Ancient World. Ann Arbor, MI: Edwards Brothers.</ref> In addition, library staff attached a small tag to the end of each scroll. These tags gave authors' names as well as other identification had been added during the accessions procedure but often no title; many a roll contained more than one work, and many works, such as compilations of poetry warranted more than a single title. When a title was lacking, Zenodotus had to enroll and pass an eye over the text. Such tags enabled the scrolls to be easily returned to the area in which they had been classified, but also ensured that library users did not have to unroll each scroll in order to see what it contained. This was the first recorded use of [[metadata]], a landmark in library history.{{sfn|Phillips|2010}} Not until the second century A.D. does fuller alphabetization make an appearance.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Homeric scholarship]]\n*[[Alexandrine grammarians]]\n*[[Library of Alexandria]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist|refs=\n{{efn|name=\"Two Others|There appear to have been at least two other grammarians of the same name:\n#''Zenodotus of Alexandria'', surnamed {{lang|grc|\u1f41 \u1f10\u03bd \u1f04\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9}} (''ho en astei'', \"the one from the city\", i.e. Alexandria)\n#''Zenodotus of Mallus'', the disciple of [[Crates of Mallus|Crates]], who like his master attacked [[Aristarchus of Samothrace]]}}\n}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal|last=Phillips |first=Heather A. |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/libphilprac/417/ |title=The Great Library of Alexandria? |journal=Library Philosophy and Practice |date=August 2010 |issn=1522-0222 |ref=harv}}\n\n'''Attribution:'''\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Zenodotus |volume=28 |page=972}} Endnotes:\n** [[Friedrich August Wolf|F. A. Wolf]], ''[[Prolegomena ad Homerum]]'', section 43 (1859 edition)\n** [[Johann Heinrich Joseph D\u00fcntzer|H. D\u00fcntzer]], ''De Zenodoti studiis Homericis'' (1848)\n** A. R\u00f6mer, ''\u00dcber die Homerrecension des Zenodotus'' (Munich, 1885)\n** [[Franz Susemihl|F. Susemihl]], ''Geschichte der griechischen Litteratur in der Alexandrinerzeit'', i. p.&nbsp;330, ii. p.&nbsp;14\n** [[John Sandys (classicist)|J. E. Sandys]], ''Hist. of Class. Schol. (1906), ed. 2, vol. i. pp.&nbsp;119\u2013121.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite CE1913|wstitle=Alexandrian Library}}\n*{{cite book |first=R. |last=Pfeiffer |year=1968 |title=History of Classical Scholarship |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofclassic0000pfei_r5h8 |url-access=registration |location=Oxford |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofclassic0000pfei_r5h8/page/105 105\u201322]}}\n*{{cite book |first=L.D. |last=Reynolds |first2=N.G. |last2=Wilson |year=1991 |title=Scribes and Scholars |edition=3rd |location= Oxford |pages=8\u201312}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Head of the [[Library of Alexandria]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Apollonius of Rhodes]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n__NOTOC__\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{EB1911 article with no significant updates}} <!-- other than the possibly spurious paragraph on the librarian. -->\n\n[[Category:Ancient Greek grammarians]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek educators]]\n[[Category:Homeric scholarship]]\n[[Category:Textual scholarship]]\n[[Category:Librarians of Alexandria]]\n[[Category:Literary critics]]\n[[Category:Ancient Ephesians]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC poets]]\n[[Category:Epigrammatists of the Greek Anthology]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the grammarian|the Neoplatonist philosopher|Zenodotus (philosopher)|the Stoic philosopher|Zenodotus (Stoic)|}}\n\n'''Zenodotus''' ({{lang-grc-gre|\u0396\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2}}) was a [[Greek language|Greek]] grammarian, [[literary critic]], [[Homeric scholarship|Homeric scholar]], and the first [[librarian]] of the [[Library of Alexandria]].{{efn|name=\"Two Others}} A native of [[Ephesus]] (today, the village of [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sel%C3%A7uk Sel\u0188uk] in western Turkey) and a pupil of [[Philitas of Cos]], he lived during the reigns of the first two [[Ptolemaic dynasty|Ptolemies]], and was at the height of his reputation about 280 BC.\n\n==Biography==\nZenodotus was the first superintendent of the [[Library of Alexandria]] and the first critical editor ({{lang|grc|\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b8\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2}} ''diorth\u014dtes'') of [[Homer]]. In 284 BC the Ptolemaic court appointed Zenodotus as first Director of the library and also the official tutor to the royal children. His colleagues in the librarianship were [[Alexander Aetolus|Alexander of Aetolia]] and [[Lycophron of Chalcis]], to whom were allotted the tragic and comic writers respectively, Homer and other epic poets being assigned to Zenodotus.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=973}}\n\nAlthough he has been reproached with arbitrariness and an insufficient knowledge of Greek, his recension undoubtedly laid a sound foundation for future criticism. Having collated the different manuscripts in the library, he expunged or obelized doubtful verses, transposed or altered lines, and introduced new readings. It is probable that he was responsible for the division of the Homeric poems into twenty-four books each, and possibly was the author of the calculation of the days of the ''Iliad'' in the ''[[Tabula Iliaca]]''.<ref>Zenodotus, of Ephesus. (1995). In Merriam Webster's Encyclopedia of Literature. Springfield, MA: Merriam-Webster.<ref>\n\nHe does not appear to have written any regular commentary on Homer, but his Homeric {{lang|grc|\u03b3\u03bb\u1ff6\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03b9}} (''[[wikt:\u03b3\u03bb\u1ff6\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1|gl\u014dssai]]'', \"lists of unusual words, [[gloss (annotation)|glosses]]\") probably formed the source of the explanations of Homer attributed by the grammarians to Zenodotus. He also lectured upon [[Hesiod]], [[Anacreon (poet)|Anacreon]] and [[Pindar]], if he did not publish editions of them. He is further called an epic poet by the ''[[Suda]],'' and three epigrams in the ''[[Greek Anthology]]'' are assigned to him.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=973}}\n\nIn addition to his other scholarly work, Zenodotus introduced an organization system on the materials in the [[Library of Alexandria]] whereby texts were assigned to different rooms based on their subject matter- verse or prose, literary or scientific, and the various sub-classifications within each. Within their subjects, Zenodotus organized the works [[Alphabetical order|alphabetically]] by the first letter of the name of their author. The principle of alphabetic organization was introduced by Zenodotus.<ref>Casson, L. (2001). Libraries in the Ancient World. Ann Arbor, MI: Edwards Brothers.</ref> In addition, library staff attached a small tag to the end of each scroll. These tags gave authors' names as well as other identification had been added during the accessions procedure but often no title; many a roll contained more than one work, and many works, such as compilations of poetry warranted more than a single title. When a title was lacking, Zenodotus had to enroll and pass an eye over the text. Such tags enabled the scrolls to be easily returned to the area in which they had been classified, but also ensured that library users did not have to unroll each scroll in order to see what it contained. This was the first recorded use of [[metadata]], a landmark in library history.{{sfn|Phillips|2010}} Not until the second century A.D. does fuller alphabetization make an appearance.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Homeric scholarship]]\n*[[Alexandrine grammarians]]\n*[[Library of Alexandria]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist|refs=\n{{efn|name=\"Two Others|There appear to have been at least two other grammarians of the same name:\n#''Zenodotus of Alexandria'', surnamed {{lang|grc|\u1f41 \u1f10\u03bd \u1f04\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9}} (''ho en astei'', \"the one from the city\", i.e. Alexandria)\n#''Zenodotus of Mallus'', the disciple of [[Crates of Mallus|Crates]], who like his master attacked [[Aristarchus of Samothrace]]}}\n}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal|last=Phillips |first=Heather A. |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/libphilprac/417/ |title=The Great Library of Alexandria? |journal=Library Philosophy and Practice |date=August 2010 |issn=1522-0222 |ref=harv}}\n\n'''Attribution:'''\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Zenodotus |volume=28 |page=972}} Endnotes:\n** [[Friedrich August Wolf|F. A. Wolf]], ''[[Prolegomena ad Homerum]]'', section 43 (1859 edition)\n** [[Johann Heinrich Joseph D\u00fcntzer|H. D\u00fcntzer]], ''De Zenodoti studiis Homericis'' (1848)\n** A. R\u00f6mer, ''\u00dcber die Homerrecension des Zenodotus'' (Munich, 1885)\n** [[Franz Susemihl|F. Susemihl]], ''Geschichte der griechische